1
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:16,000
(tugboat whistles)

2
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:57,000
(seagulls screeching)

3
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:36,000
(seagulls screeching)

4
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:24,000
(puppies whimpering)

5
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:27,000
Look at those feet.

6
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:29,000
Does that mean...

7
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Yeah, he's going
to be a big one.

8
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:32,000
Wow.
What do you say?

9
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:33,000
Thank you.

10
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Thanks, Sam.
You take good
care of him.

11
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:38,000
Bring him back in a couple
of weeks for vaccinations, okay?

12
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:40,000
Hi, Lydia.
Hi.

13
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:41,000
Bye now.

14
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:42,000
Bye-bye.
Thanks.

15
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:45,000
Which one did she take?

16
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:46,000
The floppy-eared one.

17
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:48,000
How're you doing?
I know.

18
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:51,000
Good.
Almost finished.

19
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:52,000
Want to go see
the Taj Mahal?

20
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:55,000
I'll go anywhere with you, baby.

21
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:58,000
Oh, you picked
my favorite one.

22
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:02,000
If I might be so bold,
I called him Bentley.

23
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:07,000
Get out of there.

24
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:08,000
All right.
All right.

25
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:11,000
How am I supposed to know
when my next appointment is?

26
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:13,000
Oh, it's in
a half an hour,

27
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:15,000
but it's Elmer.

28
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:17,000
If he's on time,
I'll do cartwheels.

29
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:18,000
I'd like to see that.

30
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:21,000
No, you wouldn't.

31
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:24,000
(hammering)

32
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:26,000
(saw buzzing)

33
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:41,000
I thought they'd be
further along.

34
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:43,000
We've had a lot of rain.

35
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:44,000
Hey, Sam.

36
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:45,000
Lyddie.

37
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:46,000
Hi.
What's up?

38
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:48,000
Came to take a look.

39
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:49,000
What do you think?

40
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:50,000
Nice hole.

41
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:52,000
Well, we've had
a lot of rain.

42
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:53,000
That's what I said.

43
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:54,000
Can't dig in the rain.

44
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:56,000
You guys in a hurry?

45
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:59,000
You want to fill this house
up with some babies?

46
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Yup.

47
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:02,000
Someday.

48
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:07,000
We get some good weather,
we'll be fine.

49
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:08,000
Sure.

50
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:27,000
I've got
the Turleys' sheep,

51
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:29,000
and then a checkup
on Joe's pregnant cow.

52
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:31,000
Okay. Call me when
you're headed home.
Bye.

53
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:52,000
Hi, Sam.
Hi.

54
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:53,000
How's your dog doing, Brad?

55
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:54,000
He's looking good, Doc.

56
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:56,000
Dermatitis is
practically all gone.

57
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:58,000
Yeah, but he's got
a rash of his own. Show him.

58
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,000
He wants to use
the dog medicine.

59
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,000
I wouldn't do that.

60
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:04,000
I told him that.

61
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:05,000
Why? Won't it work?

62
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:07,000
Not unless you want
to wake up one morning

63
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:08,000
barking like a dog.

64
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:10,000
That would be
an improvement.

65
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:11,000
Wouldn't it?

66
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:12,000
See ya.

67
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:39,000
Hey, kid!

68
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:40,000
Get over here and help me.

69
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:48,000
Hurry!

70
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:52,000
Come here!

71
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:54,000
Come on!

72
00:05:54,000 --> 00:05:56,000
Get up here! Ooh!

73
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:58,000
(playfully grunting)

74
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:00,000
(laughing)

75
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:07,000
Tetracycline.

76
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:11,000
Campbell's hound
lacerated his paw.

77
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:13,000
Did you find it?

78
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:15,000
No.

79
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:17,000
Where is it?

80
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:20,000
Tiny hairline fracture,
right above the joint.

81
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:21,000
Hmm.

82
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:23,000
You don't need
reading glasses, do you?

83
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:25,000
No.

84
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:27,000
Just wondering.

85
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:35,000
Hi.

86
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:36,000
Hey.
What's up?

87
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:39,000
Oh, just passing by.

88
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:42,000
I thought
I'd stop in.

89
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:44,000
Busy?

90
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:46,000
Yeah.

91
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:52,000
Don't mean to interrupt.

92
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:53,000
I saw her.

93
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:54,000
How come you
didn't tell me?

94
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:55,000
I was on a call.

95
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:58,000
I saw her, too.
Down at the gas station.

96
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Hi, Ross.

97
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:01,000
Need some help?

98
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:02,000
Elmer just showed up

99
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:04,000
and I've got
the Campbell dog.

100
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:05,000
Elmer's appointment
was yesterday.

101
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:06,000
That's Elmer.

102
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:08,000
All right.
You take him, would you?

103
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:09,000
I'll take the Campbell dog.

104
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:11,000
What brings
you here?

105
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:13,000
He needs a distemper shot.

106
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:18,000
She asked about you.

107
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:21,000
I'll catch up with her.

108
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:49,000
Trooper!

109
00:07:56,000 --> 00:07:58,000
Look what I found.

110
00:07:58,000 --> 00:07:59,000
What is it?

111
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:01,000
What do you mean,
"What is it?"

112
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:04,000
A drum set, doofus.

113
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:07,000
Whose are they?

114
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:08,000
They belonged to
an old friend of mine.

115
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:10,000
What was his name?

116
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:11,000
Ben.

117
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:13,000
He asked me to
keep them for him,

118
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:15,000
because he didn't have room.

119
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:17,000
Can I play them?

120
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:19,000
Can I play them really loud?

121
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:21,000
Yeah...

122
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:24,000
Just do me a favor

123
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:26,000
and wait till
I get downstairs.

124
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:36,000
Let 'er rip!

125
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:51,000
So what'd you think?

126
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:52,000
About what?

127
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:54,000
The movie.

128
00:08:54,000 --> 00:08:55,000
Oh, I liked it.

129
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:57,000
You did not.

130
00:08:57,000 --> 00:08:59,000
Why do you say that?

131
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:02,000
You kept looking
at your watch.

132
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:04,000
I guess I did, didn't I.

133
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:10,000
Sam, where are you?

134
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:12,000
I'm right here.

135
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:17,000
That ought
to do it, Walter.

136
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:18,000
Just give it
a week or so.

137
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:21,000
I can't pay you
till next week, Sam.

138
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:23,000
Don't look at me.
We know where you live.

139
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:27,000
Your 3:30 cancelled.

140
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:32,000
I guess I'll run out to Joe's,
check on that cow.

141
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:34,000
Weren't you just there
yesterday?

142
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:36,000
Yeah.

143
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:37,000
She's very close.

144
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:40,000
You're acting like
an expectant father.

145
00:09:40,000 --> 00:09:42,000
Are you going
to hand out cigars?

146
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:12,000
(ball bouncing)

147
00:10:22,000 --> 00:10:25,000
Hi.

148
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:27,000
Your mom around?
No.

149
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:31,000
She went to the store.

150
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:32,000
My name's Sam.

151
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:34,000
I'm an old friend
of your mother's.

152
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:44,000
I used to live next door.

153
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:46,000
This was my house, right here.

154
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:47,000
That was my room, right there.

155
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:54,000
I see you're quite
the basketball player.

156
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:55,000
Mm.

157
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:00,000
(grunts)

158
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:01,000
How about that?

159
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:07,000
Well...

160
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:11,000
I'll just...

161
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:12,000
I'll come around
another time.

162
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:22,000
ROSEMARY:
Okay, Joe.

163
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:23,000
I'll tell him.

164
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:24,000
Okay.

165
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:26,000
Okay!

166
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:27,000
Where's Sam?

167
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:29,000
Oh, I don't know.

168
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:32,000
He said he was going to
check on Joe Lieber's cow.

169
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:34,000
Maybe she's already
had her calf.

170
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:36,000
Well, she did.

171
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:37,000
But Sam wasn't there.

172
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:47,000
Where'd you go?

173
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:53,000
Well, I had to go
check on Joe's cow.

174
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:55,000
Joe called.

175
00:11:55,000 --> 00:11:56,000
The cow had her calf.

176
00:11:56,000 --> 00:11:57,000
He said you
weren't there.

177
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:02,000
Ah, I didn't make it, so...

178
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:03,000
How come?

179
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:06,000
Is Sam back?

180
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:09,000
Oh, Sam, someone
wants to see you.

181
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:10,000
Right.

182
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:18,000
I think we've solved
the mystery.

183
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:20,000
That dog's cute.

184
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:29,000
Hi, Sam.

185
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:41,000
Kind of expected
a bigger hello.

186
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:45,000
I'm... surprised to see you.

187
00:12:45,000 --> 00:12:48,000
Trooper, is this
the guy who stopped by?

188
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:49,000
Mm-hmm.

189
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:51,000
Well, I-I heard that
you were in town.

190
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:53,000
I'm just...

191
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:55,000
surprised.

192
00:12:57,000 --> 00:12:59,000
So, you already met
my son, Trooper.

193
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:01,000
No, not officially.

194
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:03,000
I'm Sam.
Hi.

195
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:04,000
Dude, what do you do
when somebody

196
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:06,000
offers you
their hand?

197
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:09,000
And what else?

198
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:10,000
Nice to meet you.

199
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:13,000
Nice to meet
you, too.

200
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:16,000
I told Troop that
you were a veterinarian,

201
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:18,000
and he wanted
to come by right away

202
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:20,000
'cause he loves animals.

203
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:22,000
Is that right?

204
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:24,000
Well...

205
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:27,000
I might know a puppy
who needs a home.

206
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:29,000
I don't suppose
you'd be interested?

207
00:13:29,000 --> 00:13:31,000
Please, Mom?

208
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:33,000
Mmm, well...
Come on.

209
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:35,000
you have to take care of him.

210
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:37,000
I will. Come on.

211
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:39,000
All right.

212
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:41,000
Just wait
right here.

213
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:44,000
Do you even know how
to take care of a dog?

214
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:45,000
What are you gonna do?

215
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:57,000
Made a deal.

216
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:07,000
A gummy bear!

217
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:08,000
You want another?

218
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:09,000
Okay.

219
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:11,000
I'm Rosemary.
Trooper.

220
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:12,000
Ah.

221
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:14,000
Oh...

222
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:17,000
Sam.
Oh.

223
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:20,000
Hey... oh...

224
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:22,000
(Rosemary and Trooper laugh)

225
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:24,000
TROOPER:
What's his name?

226
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:25,000
No, it's up to you.

227
00:14:25,000 --> 00:14:29,000
Thanks, Sam-- I think.
Just be good to him--
bring him back here

228
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:31,000
whenever he needs anything;
it'll be on the house.

229
00:14:31,000 --> 00:14:33,000
(laughs):
I'll take good care of him. Hey!

230
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:37,000
Oh, come on. Oh...

231
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:38,000
Good girl.

232
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:39,000
SAM:
Hi, Alice.

233
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:41,000
Go ahead and take her
on back to number two.

234
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:43,000
I'll be there
in a minute.

235
00:14:43,000 --> 00:14:44,000
Yes, I...
Alice?

236
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:48,000
It's me, Dee Dee.

237
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:49,000
Dee Dee Michaud?

238
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:52,000
Yeah. And this is
my son, Trooper.

239
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:55,000
Well, hello, Trooper.

240
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:58,000
Why, my goodness,
I haven't seen you since...

241
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:00,000
Yeah. About 13 years.

242
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:01,000
Are you just visiting?

243
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:02,000
No. I'm here to stay.

244
00:15:02,000 --> 00:15:07,000
Well... good for you.

245
00:15:09,000 --> 00:15:10,000
Sam, I-I can see
that you're busy--

246
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:11,000
we'll catch up later?

247
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:14,000
Okay.
Okay.

248
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:15,000
(quietly):
Trooper!

249
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:17,000
Thanks for the puppy.
You're welcome.

250
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:20,000
Bye, Rosemary.
Good-bye.

251
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:22,000
SAM:
Give him a good home.

252
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:24,000
I will.

253
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:41,000
(crickets chirping)

254
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:45,000
LYDIA:
Why didn't you just tell me
the truth at the office?

255
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:47,000
I didn't want
Rosemary gossiping.

256
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:48,000
About what?

257
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:49,000
About Dee Dee.

258
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:51,000
What about Dee Dee?

259
00:15:51,000 --> 00:15:52,000
(groans):
Oh, just... nothing.

260
00:15:52,000 --> 00:15:55,000
You were worried she'd
gossip about nothing?

261
00:15:55,000 --> 00:15:56,000
We were friends.

262
00:15:56,000 --> 00:15:58,000
We grew up together--
I mean, I've known

263
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:00,000
the girl since I was
three years old.

264
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:02,000
She and Ross
and I hung out.

265
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:04,000
I mean, she was fun.

266
00:16:04,000 --> 00:16:05,000
Fun?

267
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:08,000
We were just
friends, okay?
(laughs)

268
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:10,000
People gossip
about friends here.

269
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:12,000
It's a small town, Lydia.

270
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:13,000
What do you know
about small towns--

271
00:16:13,000 --> 00:16:14,000
you grew up in Boston.
Oh, I don't know, Sam,

272
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:16,000
why don't you tell me
what it's like to grow up

273
00:16:16,000 --> 00:16:18,000
in a small town.

274
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:19,000
Tell me about your "friend."
What do you mean?

275
00:16:19,000 --> 00:16:21,000
I don't know.
What's she like?

276
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:23,000
She was a free spirit.

277
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:26,000
'Kay? Everybody in town
knew her.

278
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:32,000
Me, I was this shy little kid
afraid of his own shadow.

279
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:35,000
Once there was
this kid who was...

280
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:39,000
sort of the neighborhood bully,
he stole my baseball cards.

281
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:40,000
Now, I pretended
that it didn't matter,

282
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:42,000
but it mattered to Dee Dee.

283
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:45,000
She found him,
she beat him up,

284
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:47,000
and she got 'em all back for me.
Oh, that was nice of her.

285
00:16:47,000 --> 00:16:50,000
But you know what,
she didn't even care

286
00:16:50,000 --> 00:16:53,000
about what people thought
about her.

287
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:54,000
In the ninth grade,

288
00:16:54,000 --> 00:16:56,000
she gets caught smoking
in the school bathroom.

289
00:16:56,000 --> 00:16:57,000
The principal

290
00:16:57,000 --> 00:16:59,000
takes her into his office.

291
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:01,000
Before he can even
get a word in,

292
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:03,000
she offers him a cigarette.

293
00:17:03,000 --> 00:17:05,000
Mm-hmm.

294
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:10,000
Anyway...

295
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:12,000
on graduation day, she ran off

296
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:14,000
with Bobby Langford.

297
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:17,000
Could you pass me
the olive oil?

298
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:20,000
Is she the one

299
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:23,000
you were gonna give
your class ring to?

300
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:25,000
Who told you that?

301
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:26,000
Ross.

302
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:28,000
A long time ago.

303
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:31,000
Yeah. She was the one.

304
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:34,000
Pass me the pepper?

305
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:39,000
Not until you tell me.

306
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:40,000
Nothing to tell.

307
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:42,000
Try me.

308
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:53,000
Well, I was planning on
giving her my class ring

309
00:17:53,000 --> 00:17:55,000
the night before
graduation.

310
00:17:55,000 --> 00:17:56,000
We were standing
out on her porch,

311
00:17:56,000 --> 00:17:59,000
and I had it out,
I had it in my hand,

312
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:01,000
and I'm about to give
it to her, but before
I could say anything,

313
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:04,000
she pops out with the
news that she's going.

314
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:05,000
Next day, gone.

315
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:07,000
You never heard from her?

316
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:08,000
Couple of postcards.

317
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:11,000
Uh, one.

318
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:14,000
From some small
town in Kansas.

319
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:16,000
Home of the world's
biggest ball of twine.

320
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:18,000
"Ain't life a hoot?"

321
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:21,000
That's what it said,
nothing more.

322
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:27,000
How come
you never mentioned her?

323
00:18:29,000 --> 00:18:32,000
I didn't think it
was that important.

324
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:48,000
It's just that
she was your first crush.

325
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:51,000
I mean, if my first
boyfriend came into town...

326
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:53,000
Look, I...

327
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:56,000
I got over it.

328
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:01,000
I married this woman that
I am absolutely crazy about.

329
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:03,000
Really? What's she like?

330
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:06,000
Eh, you'd have to know her.

331
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:08,000
Is she pretty?

332
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:10,000
Pretty? No.

333
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:13,000
Movie-star beautiful.

334
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:15,000
Smart as a whip.

335
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:18,000
And let's see...
terrific veterinarian.

336
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:19,000
Did I mention that?

337
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:22,000
Loved by people
and pets alike.

338
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:28,000
I think we should
ask them to dinner.

339
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:30,000
Really?

340
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:33,000
You got to know
the competition.

341
00:19:49,000 --> 00:19:50,000
Oops.

342
00:19:51,000 --> 00:19:53,000
Hi!
Hey, Dee Dee,
Trooper.

343
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:55,000
Lydia.
Nice to meet you.

344
00:19:55,000 --> 00:19:57,000
Hi. Nice to meet you, too.
This is Trooper.

345
00:19:57,000 --> 00:19:58,000
Hi, Trooper.

346
00:19:58,000 --> 00:19:59,000
Hi.

347
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:01,000
(tsks)

348
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:04,000
Hi. It is really nice

349
00:20:04,000 --> 00:20:05,000
to meet you.

350
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:07,000
Well, come on inside.

351
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:13,000
This is for you.

352
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:16,000
Oh. Thank you.
Should I open it now?

353
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:18,000
Sure.
Okay.

354
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:19,000
(Lydia chuckles)

355
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:26,000
Oh, they're lovely.

356
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:28,000
(laughs):
I'm glad you like them.

357
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:29,000
I made them.

358
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:33,000
Uh, they're beautiful.
(laughs)

359
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:36,000
We can use them
tonight at dinner.

360
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:37,000
I'm still working
in the kitchen.

361
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:38,000
Oh, good.
Let me help you.

362
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:45,000
What are you making?
Nothing fancy.

363
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:48,000
Some roasted chicken,
mash potatoes, carrots.

364
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:55,000
Nut?

365
00:20:55,000 --> 00:20:57,000
Okay.

366
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:02,000
LYDIA:
Oh, I love candlelight dinners.

367
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:03,000
Mmm, me, too.

368
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:05,000
Maybe you'll be
a customer.

369
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:06,000
A customer?

370
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:08,000
I'm gonna open up
a candle shop.

371
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:11,000
Here?
Is that a bad idea?

372
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:13,000
Well, no...
it's not a bad idea.

373
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:15,000
(chuckles):
But...?

374
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:20,000
He's such a terrible liar.

375
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:22,000
He's learning.

376
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:26,000
Well, I just...
wonder if it's, uh,

377
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:29,000
if the town is
large enough for a...

378
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:31,000
a candle store.
Yeah, I thought
of that, but...

379
00:21:31,000 --> 00:21:34,000
I figure if I offer
candle-making lessons,
you know.

380
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:35,000
What do you think
Lydia?

381
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:38,000
Oh, I-I think you'll just
have to try it and see.

382
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:41,000
Well, would you be interested?

383
00:21:41,000 --> 00:21:43,000
Me? I don't have
that much free time.

384
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:50,000
So, how did you get interested

385
00:21:50,000 --> 00:21:51,000
in candle-making?

386
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:55,000
Oh, you know, it started
as a hobby, but then

387
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:56,000
I had to make a living.

388
00:21:56,000 --> 00:22:00,000
And, uh... I guess I just love
what candles symbolize.

389
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:03,000
Which is what?

390
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:04,000
Home.

391
00:22:04,000 --> 00:22:05,000
I guess hopes

392
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:09,000
and dreams and wishes.

393
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:11,000
People light candles in church.

394
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:12,000
They use them
for prayer.

395
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:14,000
Dude,

396
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:16,000
you can't just eat
before everybody starts.

397
00:22:16,000 --> 00:22:18,000
No, it's okay. It's okay.

398
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:19,000
Dig in.

399
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:20,000
(clears throat)

400
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:22,000
So, Trooper...

401
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:24,000
how'd you get the
nickname "Trooper"?

402
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:26,000
It's not a nickname.

403
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:29,000
It's my real name.
We've traveled around

404
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:32,000
so much, we're like
a small theater troupe.

405
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:34,000
So you spell it with a "U"?

406
00:22:34,000 --> 00:22:37,000
Hmm?
T-R-O-U-P-E-R.

407
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:38,000
No...

408
00:22:38,000 --> 00:22:41,000
T-R-O-O-P-E-R.

409
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:42,000
I gave him the name,

410
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:44,000
so I figure he can
spell it however he wants.

411
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:46,000
Well, not really.

412
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:50,000
Oh. Yeah, that's right, because
last year you wanted to spell it

413
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:52,000
with three O's.
(laughs)

414
00:22:59,000 --> 00:23:03,000
Troop, weren't you gonna
ask Sam something?

415
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:05,000
Oh, yeah.

416
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:07,000
Uh...

417
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:09,000
do you have lots
of animals downstairs?

418
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:10,000
We sure do.

419
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:12,000
Can I see 'em?

420
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:16,000
Sam, why don't you take Trooper
down and show him our zoo.

421
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:17,000
Good.

422
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:19,000
All right,
come on, Troop.

423
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:21,000
Can I call you Troop?
If you want to.

424
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:24,000
Everybody
calls me Sam.

425
00:23:24,000 --> 00:23:26,000
He's a nice boy.

426
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:27,000
Yeah.

427
00:23:27,000 --> 00:23:29,000
He reminds me
of Sam.

428
00:23:29,000 --> 00:23:33,000
Shy at first, but there's
a lot going on underneath.

429
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:36,000
I understand you're living
in your childhood home.

430
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:39,000
Yeah. Lots of
memories there.

431
00:23:39,000 --> 00:23:41,000
(chuckles)

432
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:43,000
What brings you back
after all this time

433
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:47,000
My mom died, and the house

434
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:49,000
was just sitting there.

435
00:23:49,000 --> 00:23:51,000
But mostly for Trooper--
I keep boring him

436
00:23:51,000 --> 00:23:56,000
with all my stories of how
great it was to grow up here.

437
00:23:56,000 --> 00:23:57,000
How'd you and Sam meet?

438
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:00,000
Oh, at Cornell, in vet school.

439
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:03,000
He always wanted
to be a vet.

440
00:24:03,000 --> 00:24:06,000
I guess you knew him
pretty well.

441
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:09,000
Yeah. Hard not to--
he lived next-door.

442
00:24:09,000 --> 00:24:11,000
We spent every
day together.

443
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:14,000
Especially in
the summertime.

444
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:17,000
So you moved back here
after vet school?

445
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:20,000
I was a city girl
pining for country life.

446
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:22,000
Slower pace,

447
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:24,000
nicer people.

448
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:27,000
You must have a lot
of friends here.

449
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:30,000
Yeah, I... I guess I do.

450
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:32,000
But you married my best one.

451
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:44,000
Well, this is where we operate.

452
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:49,000
Is there a lot
of blood and stuff?

453
00:24:49,000 --> 00:24:51,000
Sometimes.

454
00:24:51,000 --> 00:24:53,000
How's that puppy
doing, by the way?

455
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:55,000
Oh, he's fine.

456
00:24:55,000 --> 00:24:57,000
What do you
call him?

457
00:24:57,000 --> 00:24:59,000
Chewbacca.

458
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:00,000
Nice name.

459
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:02,000
How did you come up with that?

460
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:05,000
He tried to eat
my shoelaces.

461
00:25:05,000 --> 00:25:09,000
Are all these yours?

462
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:11,000
No. They all belong
to other people.

463
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:14,000
Except this
little guy.

464
00:25:14,000 --> 00:25:18,000
Actually, this is
Chewbacca's brother.

465
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:20,000
Want to see him?

466
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:22,000
Sure.

467
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:24,000
Do you get to
play with them?

468
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:26,000
It's kind of hard
to find the time.

469
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:31,000
Thank you.
Dinner was so good.

470
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:32,000
You're welcome.

471
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:34,000
Do you want me to
walk you guys home?

472
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:36,000
Nah. We know the way.
Don't bother.

473
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:39,000
Go ahead, Sam.

474
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:43,000
I'll be right back.

475
00:25:43,000 --> 00:25:44,000
Got it?
Yep.

476
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:49,000
Remember that
bike I bought

477
00:25:49,000 --> 00:25:52,000
with berry-picking
money?

478
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:57,000
The one you sold
to Jimmy Farrington?

479
00:25:57,000 --> 00:25:58,000
I wish I had it back.

480
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:00,000
I'd give it to Troop.

481
00:26:00,000 --> 00:26:01,000
What's wrong
with the one he has?

482
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:04,000
Nothing. Just
pure nostalgia.

483
00:26:04,000 --> 00:26:06,000
Nostalgia?

484
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:09,000
Coming from the woman who could
not wait to get out of here.

485
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:11,000
It's funny,
isn't it?

486
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:13,000
Guess it's true
you never appreciate

487
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:16,000
what you have
until it's gone.

488
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:18,000
Hey, Trooper.

489
00:26:18,000 --> 00:26:22,000
This is Cee Jay's--
that place I told you about.

490
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:24,000
Same old place.

491
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:26,000
Same old geezers.

492
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:28,000
Except now I'm one of them.

493
00:26:33,000 --> 00:26:36,000
Where's his dad?

494
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:39,000
Troop never knew his dad.

495
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:42,000
He was less than
a year old when Bobby left.

496
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:43,000
Bobby?

497
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:46,000
Yeah.

498
00:26:46,000 --> 00:26:48,000
Where did he go?

499
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:51,000
Alaska.

500
00:26:51,000 --> 00:26:53,000
He never really
wanted kids.

501
00:26:53,000 --> 00:26:56,000
I can't say that
I'm surprised.

502
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:00,000
Sam, is that a polite way
of saying, "I told you so"?

503
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:03,000
How about
you and Lydia?

504
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:06,000
Any plans for kids
in the future?

505
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:10,000
Kids? Yeah. Someday.

506
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:12,000
I just want
to be sure.

507
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:14,000
Sure about what?

508
00:27:15,000 --> 00:27:17,000
We're financially
secure.

509
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:19,000
That we're ready.

510
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:21,000
Time to devote
to a family.

511
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:23,000
You haven't
changed a bit, Sam.

512
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:25,000
I guess not.

513
00:27:25,000 --> 00:27:28,000
I wish I were
more like you.

514
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:30,000
Never thought I'd
hear you say that.

515
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:31,000
Oh, shut up.

516
00:27:31,000 --> 00:27:34,000
I have learned something
in the last 13 years.

517
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:53,000
Last few nights, I can't sleep.

518
00:27:53,000 --> 00:27:58,000
I wake up, I go to my window
and look out at your window.

519
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:00,000
It used to make me
so comfortable,

520
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:02,000
just knowing
you were there.

521
00:28:07,000 --> 00:28:09,000
I'm so sorry, Sam.

522
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:12,000
I'm sorry
I fell off the map.

523
00:28:12,000 --> 00:28:14,000
Bobby and I
married right away.

524
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:16,000
Trooper came
a year later.

525
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:20,000
I'm not making excuses, but...

526
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:22,000
I do really apologize.

527
00:28:22,000 --> 00:28:23,000
No need.

528
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:30,000
It's kind of hard for Troop,
you know,

529
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:32,000
moving again to a new place.

530
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:35,000
He's got to make new friends.

531
00:28:35,000 --> 00:28:37,000
He seems
like a great kid.

532
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:39,000
You know,
in the meantime,

533
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:41,000
I could use some help
around the clinic.

534
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:44,000
Someone to feed and
look after the animals.

535
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:46,000
He would love that.

536
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:47,000
Thank you, Sam.

537
00:28:47,000 --> 00:28:49,000
I... I... I have
to make trips

538
00:28:49,000 --> 00:28:50,000
back and forth
to Boston...

539
00:28:50,000 --> 00:28:52,000
This is perfect.

540
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:54,000
What are you doing in Boston?

541
00:28:54,000 --> 00:28:57,000
Oh, I have to pick up supplies.

542
00:28:57,000 --> 00:29:02,000
Umm... Lydia seems great.

543
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:05,000
Yeah, she is great.

544
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:07,000
