00:42:42,000 --> 00:42:45,000
The kid thinks he's
some sort of romantic hero.

818
00:42:45,000 --> 00:42:48,000
I couldn't even believe
what I was hearing.

819
00:42:48,000 --> 00:42:50,000
A dreamer?

820
00:42:50,000 --> 00:42:51,000
Come on.

821
00:42:51,000 --> 00:42:55,000
The guy was a lowlife
who abandoned them.

822
00:42:55,000 --> 00:42:57,000
Maybe you were just a little
jealous of him, Sam.

823
00:42:57,000 --> 00:42:59,000
Lyddie,
the guy spent

824
00:42:59,000 --> 00:43:01,000
half the year he was
here working on his car,

825
00:43:01,000 --> 00:43:03,000
the other half dealing pot.

826
00:43:03,000 --> 00:43:04,000
How do you
romanticize that?

827
00:43:06,000 --> 00:43:09,000
What if she's just
protecting her son?

828
00:43:09,000 --> 00:43:12,000
By lying to him?

829
00:43:12,000 --> 00:43:14,000
If he were your son,
what would you say?

830
00:43:21,000 --> 00:43:22,000
I don't know.

831
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:40,000
Well, looky!

832
00:43:40,000 --> 00:43:41,000
Hey, Cee Jay.

833
00:43:41,000 --> 00:43:42,000
How you doing?

834
00:43:42,000 --> 00:43:44,000
I heard you were
back in town.

835
00:43:44,000 --> 00:43:46,000
Yeah. You want to check
my ID for old times' sake?

836
00:43:46,000 --> 00:43:48,000
Darling, you
never had an ID.

837
00:43:48,000 --> 00:43:50,000
That's how come I used
to throw you out of here.

838
00:43:50,000 --> 00:43:51,000
Nice to have you back.

839
00:43:51,000 --> 00:43:53,000
It's nice to be
here-- legally.

840
00:43:56,000 --> 00:43:57,000
Hey.
Hey, we were
wondering

841
00:43:57,000 --> 00:43:58,000
if you were
going to show up.

842
00:43:58,000 --> 00:44:00,000
Yeah, I know.
I had to drive to Boston

843
00:44:00,000 --> 00:44:02,000
to pick up supplies
for the candle business.

844
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:03,000
Oh! Candlemania
sweeps the town.

845
00:44:03,000 --> 00:44:04,000
I know.

846
00:44:04,000 --> 00:44:06,000
Even Rosemary joined the group.

847
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:08,000
Oh, no. Where
will it end?

848
00:44:08,000 --> 00:44:09,000
Maybe it won't.

849
00:44:09,000 --> 00:44:10,000
Everything ends.

850
00:44:11,000 --> 00:44:13,000
Hey, Cee Jay,
can we get another glass?

851
00:44:13,000 --> 00:44:14,000
You know what?

852
00:44:14,000 --> 00:44:16,000
We have three-fourths
of the band here.

853
00:44:16,000 --> 00:44:17,000
What band?

854
00:44:17,000 --> 00:44:18,000
Sam's band.
Oh, it wasn't

855
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:20,000
my band, it was Dee Dee's.

856
00:44:20,000 --> 00:44:21,000
I didn't know
you had a band.

857
00:44:21,000 --> 00:44:23,000
I didn't.

858
00:44:23,000 --> 00:44:24,000
I wouldn't have even
been in the band

859
00:44:24,000 --> 00:44:25,000
if Dee Dee hadn't
of browbeaten

860
00:44:25,000 --> 00:44:26,000
the others
into taking me.

861
00:44:26,000 --> 00:44:29,000
What did you play?

862
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:30,000
Guitar.

863
00:44:30,000 --> 00:44:31,000
If you call
that playing.

864
00:44:31,000 --> 00:44:32,000
I don't.

865
00:44:32,000 --> 00:44:33,000
Come on, Sam.

866
00:44:33,000 --> 00:44:34,000
People liked you.
Because you did.

867
00:44:34,000 --> 00:44:36,000
If Ben and Ross
and I would have

868
00:44:36,000 --> 00:44:37,000
started the
band on our own,

869
00:44:37,000 --> 00:44:38,000
it would have lasted
five minutes.

870
00:44:38,000 --> 00:44:40,000
Hey, I was good.

871
00:44:40,000 --> 00:44:41,000
Yeah.
You were
awful.

872
00:44:41,000 --> 00:44:43,000
Dee Dee, she
was, was good.

873
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:44,000
When did Ben move?

874
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:45,000
Um... a couple
of years ago.

875
00:44:45,000 --> 00:44:47,000
I think he went
up to Dallas.
Yeah.

876
00:44:47,000 --> 00:44:49,000
Do you still sing, Dee Dee?

877
00:44:49,000 --> 00:44:51,000
Yeah.

878
00:44:51,000 --> 00:44:52,000
It drives Trooper crazy.

879
00:44:52,000 --> 00:44:53,000
So. How about a song?

880
00:44:53,000 --> 00:44:56,000
Yeah.
Oh, we don't have Ben.

881
00:44:56,000 --> 00:44:58,000
Unless you want
to do Ben's part.

882
00:44:58,000 --> 00:45:00,000
Are you kidding?

883
00:45:00,000 --> 00:45:01,000
(Sam laughing)

884
00:45:02,000 --> 00:45:04,000
Sam, you never sang for me.

885
00:45:04,000 --> 00:45:06,000
Profoundly good reason.

886
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:13,000
♪ People say I'm the
life of the party ♪

887
00:45:13,000 --> 00:45:17,000
♪ 'Cause I tell a joke or two ♪

888
00:45:17,000 --> 00:45:23,000
♪ Although I might be
laughing loud and hearty ♪

889
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:27,000
♪ Deep inside I'm blue ♪

890
00:45:27,000 --> 00:45:32,000
♪ So take a good
look at my face ♪

891
00:45:32,000 --> 00:45:37,000
♪ You see my smile
looks out of place ♪

892
00:45:37,000 --> 00:45:41,000
♪ If you look closer,
it's easy to trace ♪

893
00:45:41,000 --> 00:45:45,000
♪ The tracks of my tears... ♪

894
00:45:45,000 --> 00:45:47,000
(drumming)

895
00:45:50,000 --> 00:45:51,000
Hey, kid!

896
00:45:51,000 --> 00:45:52,000
It's too late for drums.

897
00:45:52,000 --> 00:45:53,000
Go to bed.

898
00:45:57,000 --> 00:45:58,000
Guess what I did today?

899
00:45:58,000 --> 00:45:59,000
What's that?

900
00:45:59,000 --> 00:46:01,000
I delivered a horse.

901
00:46:01,000 --> 00:46:03,000
All by yourself?

902
00:46:03,000 --> 00:46:07,000
No, not by myself,
but I helped.

903
00:46:07,000 --> 00:46:08,000
Yeah?

904
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:10,000
It was so cool!

905
00:46:10,000 --> 00:46:14,000
And guess what else?

906
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:16,000
Sam...

907
00:46:16,000 --> 00:46:18,000
he said my dad was
a really cool guy.

908
00:46:19,000 --> 00:46:21,000
Oh.

909
00:46:21,000 --> 00:46:22,000
Yeah.

910
00:46:22,000 --> 00:46:24,000
Yeah, really cool.

911
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:25,000
Just like you,

912
00:46:25,000 --> 00:46:27,000
Mr. Horse Doctor.

913
00:46:27,000 --> 00:46:29,000
Now go to sleep!

914
00:46:29,000 --> 00:46:31,000
(smooching, giggling)

915
00:46:37,000 --> 00:46:39,000
I love you, Mom.

916
00:46:41,000 --> 00:46:43,000
I love you, too, baby.

917
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:50,000
Here's your friend.

918
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:52,000
'Night.

919
00:46:53,000 --> 00:46:54,000
Good night, angel.

920
00:46:54,000 --> 00:46:55,000
See you in the morning.

921
00:47:01,000 --> 00:47:04,000
Hey, let's go to sleep, okay?

922
00:47:25,000 --> 00:47:28,000
(sobbing)

923
00:47:36,000 --> 00:47:38,000
Guys, give me a hand
with the wall?

924
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:39,000
Let's get it up.

925
00:47:39,000 --> 00:47:42,000
Would you like some coffee, sir?

926
00:47:46,000 --> 00:47:48,000
Good. Okay, slide it.

927
00:47:50,000 --> 00:47:52,000
Looks good, Rick.

928
00:47:52,000 --> 00:47:55,000
When do you
think the framing
will be finished?

929
00:47:55,000 --> 00:47:58,000
It's hard to say.

930
00:47:58,000 --> 00:47:59,000
Can you give us a guess?

931
00:47:59,000 --> 00:48:01,000
Well... That's good.

932
00:48:01,000 --> 00:48:02,000
Not really.

933
00:48:04,000 --> 00:48:06,000
Well, by fall?

934
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:08,000
Early fall or late fall?

935
00:48:08,000 --> 00:48:09,000
Any fall.

936
00:48:09,000 --> 00:48:13,000
Depends, really.

937
00:48:13,000 --> 00:48:14,000
Well, if we get
into the winter

938
00:48:14,000 --> 00:48:15,000
and the house
isn't finished...

939
00:48:15,000 --> 00:48:16,000
Yeah, it could happen.

940
00:48:16,000 --> 00:48:18,000
Wouldn't that hurt
the house?

941
00:48:18,000 --> 00:48:19,000
Not really. Why?

942
00:48:19,000 --> 00:48:24,000
I'd just prefer it
if it didn't fall
down in a heap.

943
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:25,000
Picky, picky.

944
00:48:51,000 --> 00:48:54,000
Hey, Doc.

945
00:48:54,000 --> 00:48:55,000
How's that colt doing?

946
00:48:55,000 --> 00:48:57,000
Oh, fit and fine,
like last week.

947
00:48:57,000 --> 00:48:59,000
Not used to seeing
so much of you.

948
00:48:59,000 --> 00:49:01,000
Thank my assistant
for that.

949
00:49:01,000 --> 00:49:02,000
Oh...

950
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:05,000
What's his name?

951
00:49:05,000 --> 00:49:06,000
I don't have one yet.

952
00:49:06,000 --> 00:49:09,000
Got any ideas?

953
00:49:11,000 --> 00:49:12,000
Solitaire.

954
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:14,000
Huh. Pretty good.

955
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:15,000
How come you
picked that one?

956
00:49:15,000 --> 00:49:17,000
(whinnies)

957
00:49:17,000 --> 00:49:19,000
He doesn't have anyone
to play with.

958
00:49:19,000 --> 00:49:24,000
Well, then that's
what we'll call him.

959
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:27,000
Solitaire.

960
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:28,000
Quick, quick, quick!

961
00:49:28,000 --> 00:49:31,000
Mom, it's my fault.
Look at him!

962
00:49:31,000 --> 00:49:32,000
No, it's not,
sweetheart.

963
00:49:32,000 --> 00:49:33,000
I should have been there!

964
00:49:33,000 --> 00:49:35,000
Honey, it's okay.
Come on.

965
00:49:35,000 --> 00:49:36,000
Come on. They'll
fix him right up.

966
00:49:36,000 --> 00:49:39,000
(sobbing)

967
00:49:39,000 --> 00:49:41,000
Cody got hit by a car.

968
00:49:41,000 --> 00:49:44,000
Oh, my. Here, bring
him on back. Sam!

969
00:49:48,000 --> 00:49:50,000
What does it look like?

970
00:49:50,000 --> 00:49:52,000
Crushed lumbar vertebra.

971
00:49:52,000 --> 00:49:56,000
Spinal cord damage
looks irreversible.

972
00:49:56,000 --> 00:50:01,000
Abdomen's full of fluid,
probably a ruptured spleen.

973
00:50:01,000 --> 00:50:04,000
Maybe I'll take Amber outside
while you talk to Val.

974
00:50:04,000 --> 00:50:05,000
Okay.

975
00:50:09,000 --> 00:50:11,000
(Amber sobbing)

976
00:50:14,000 --> 00:50:16,000
Do you want to go come
outside with me?

977
00:50:21,000 --> 00:50:23,000
Hi.
Hi.

978
00:50:23,000 --> 00:50:26,000
Want to go over
the X rays?

979
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:27,000
No, that's okay.

980
00:50:27,000 --> 00:50:29,000
It looks bad, Val.

981
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:32,000
Is there anything we can do?

982
00:50:32,000 --> 00:50:36,000
Well... we could try to save
him, but it'll be painful

983
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:37,000
and I can't give you
any guarantees.

984
00:50:37,000 --> 00:50:43,000
What would you do
if he were yours, Sam?

985
00:50:43,000 --> 00:50:45,000
I think I'd let Cody go.

986
00:50:48,000 --> 00:50:50,000
Okay.

987
00:50:52,000 --> 00:50:53,000
I'm going
to talk to Amber.

988
00:50:53,000 --> 00:50:55,000
Sure.

989
00:50:55,000 --> 00:50:56,000
I'll let her come
and say good-bye.

990
00:51:03,000 --> 00:51:05,000
You're just going
to let him die?

991
00:51:05,000 --> 00:51:07,000
Well, I'd do anything
if I could save him,

992
00:51:07,000 --> 00:51:10,000
but he's been hurt
pretty badly

993
00:51:10,000 --> 00:51:13,000
and he's in a lot
of pain.

994
00:51:13,000 --> 00:51:15,000
I don't think we should
let him suffer like that.

995
00:51:21,000 --> 00:51:23,000
Troop, where are you going?

996
00:51:32,000 --> 00:51:34,000
(doorbell chimes)

997
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:39,000
Hi.
Hey.

998
00:51:39,000 --> 00:51:41,000
Is Troop home?

999
00:51:41,000 --> 00:51:43,000
Yeah, he's upstairs.

1000
00:51:43,000 --> 00:51:44,000
Can I speak with him?

1001
00:51:44,000 --> 00:51:45,000
I want to explain
something to him.

1002
00:51:45,000 --> 00:51:47,000
I already talked to him.

1003
00:51:47,000 --> 00:51:50,000
He's pretty upset.
Come on in.

1004
00:51:54,000 --> 00:51:57,000
It isn't just about
the puppy, Sam.

1005
00:51:57,000 --> 00:52:00,000
What is it?

1006
00:52:00,000 --> 00:52:03,000
You know, I've been

1007
00:52:03,000 --> 00:52:05,000
making trips back
and forth to Boston.

1008
00:52:05,000 --> 00:52:07,000
Hm-hmm.

1009
00:52:07,000 --> 00:52:11,000
It's not to pick up supplies.

1010
00:52:11,000 --> 00:52:12,000
I've been going to a hospital.

1011
00:52:13,000 --> 00:52:15,000
What for?

1012
00:52:16,000 --> 00:52:20,000
Cancer.
Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.

1013
00:52:23,000 --> 00:52:26,000
I'm dying, Sam.

1014
00:52:28,000 --> 00:52:30,000
It's widespread.

1015
00:52:30,000 --> 00:52:36,000
It's in my lymph nodes,
bone marrow,

1016
00:52:36,000 --> 00:52:38,000
liver.

1017
00:52:38,000 --> 00:52:41,000
You must have had
treatment.

1018
00:52:41,000 --> 00:52:42,000
Yeah.

1019
00:52:42,000 --> 00:52:46,000
It's just
a matter of time.

1020
00:52:46,000 --> 00:52:47,000
How much time?

1021
00:52:49,000 --> 00:52:52,000
I was hoping to make it
to Troop's 12th birthday,

1022
00:52:52,000 --> 00:52:54,000
but it's moving too fast.

1023
00:52:54,000 --> 00:52:56,000
Does he know?

1024
00:52:56,000 --> 00:52:59,000
More or less.

1025
00:52:59,000 --> 00:53:02,000
But he's hoping.

1026
00:53:02,000 --> 00:53:05,000
I haven't told him the latest.

1027
00:53:06,000 --> 00:53:12,000
Sorry. It's really why
I came home.

1028
00:53:12,000 --> 00:53:14,000
So you can die here?

1029
00:53:14,000 --> 00:53:17,000
No, I want Trooper to live here.

1030
00:53:17,000 --> 00:53:18,000
I need to find him

1031
00:53:18,000 --> 00:53:20,000
a place, a family.

1032
00:53:22,000 --> 00:53:26,000
I had this crazy idea.

1033
00:53:26,000 --> 00:53:29,000
I built this place up
in my mind, you know?

1034
00:53:29,000 --> 00:53:31,000
It seemed
so magical to me

1035
00:53:31,000 --> 00:53:35,000
and I thought all I had to do
was come home.

1036
00:53:35,000 --> 00:53:39,000
Clearly, I haven't
learned a thing

1037
00:53:39,000 --> 00:53:43,000
'cause when I was 18
I thought everything outside

1038
00:53:43,000 --> 00:53:46,000
of this town was magical,
and I just had to leave.

1039
00:53:46,000 --> 00:53:48,000
How about his dad?

1040
00:53:48,000 --> 00:53:51,000
Oh, come on.
You've never liked him.

1041
00:53:52,000 --> 00:53:55,000
You were right.

1042
00:53:55,000 --> 00:53:58,000
He got into drugs
and dealing,

1043
00:53:58,000 --> 00:54:02,000
and it only got worse
as time went on.

1044
00:54:02,000 --> 00:54:05,000
After Troop was born,
he took off for Alaska.

1045
00:54:05,000 --> 00:54:09,000
Said he had to get work.

1046
00:54:09,000 --> 00:54:15,000
He, um, got busted
and did two years.

1047
00:54:15,000 --> 00:54:19,000
Then when he got out,
he went right back to it.

1048
00:54:19,000 --> 00:54:25,000
He got himself killed,
and I never found out how.

1049
00:54:34,000 --> 00:54:37,000
I chose so badly, Sam,

1050
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:43,000
not just for myself,
but for Troop.

1051
00:54:43,000 --> 00:54:46,000
Aw, Dee Dee.

1052
00:54:46,000 --> 00:54:48,000
I'm so sorry.

1053
00:54:48,000 --> 00:54:49,000
I know.

1054
00:54:49,000 --> 00:54:51,000
I know you are.

1055
00:54:51,000 --> 00:54:53,000
I need your help, Sam.

1056
00:54:53,000 --> 00:54:56,000
I have no one else.

1057
00:54:56,000 --> 00:54:58,000
Anything.

1058
00:54:58,000 --> 00:55:03,000
I need you to help me find
a place for Troop.

1059
00:55:05,000 --> 00:55:08,000
Please?

1060
00:55:09,000 --> 00:55:12,000
I just sat there with this
stupid look on my face.

1061
00:55:12,000 --> 00:55:14,000
I felt like such an idiot.

1062
00:55:14,000 --> 00:55:18,000
But I didn't know what to say.

1063
00:55:18,000 --> 00:55:19,000
What are you going
to do?

1064
00:55:19,000 --> 00:55:21,000
I don't know.

1065
00:55:21,000 --> 00:55:23,000
Look for somebody,
I guess.

1066
00:55:23,000 --> 00:55:26,000
But who?

1067
00:55:26,000 --> 00:55:28,000
I thought
of John Frieden.

1068
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:29,000
John Frieden?

1069
00:55:29,000 --> 00:55:32,000
Yeah. He likes Trooper.
He's got horses...

1070
00:55:32,000 --> 00:55:34,000
He's over 60 years old.

1071
00:55:34,000 --> 00:55:36,000
50-something.
And Trooper would love
being on a farm.

1072
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:39,000
What does he know about
raising boys these days?

1073
00:55:39,000 --> 00:55:41,000
They raised two kids.

1074
00:55:41,000 --> 00:55:42,000
That was over ten years ago.

1075
00:55:42,000 --> 00:55:43,000
His kids are married.

1076
00:55:43,000 --> 00:55:45,000
They have families
of their own.

1077
00:55:45,000 --> 00:55:46,000
You think he's forgotten how?

1078
00:55:46,000 --> 00:55:50,000
No, but raising kids
these days

1079
00:55:50,000 --> 00:55:52,000
is a lot different
than it was then.

1080
00:55:56,000 --> 00:55:57,000
It was just a thought.

1081
00:56:01,000 --> 00:56:02,000
Sam?

1082
00:56:02,000 --> 00:56:04,000
Mm?

1083
00:56:04,000 --> 00:56:06,000
I was thinking last night.

1084
00:56:06,000 --> 00:56:08,000
Yeah? So was I.

1085
00:56:08,000 --> 00:56:09,000
About what?

1086
00:56:09,000 --> 00:56:12,000
Going over the names
of everyone I know.

1087
00:56:12,000 --> 00:56:14,000
We could take him.

1088
00:56:17,000 --> 00:56:19,000
No, we couldn't.

1089
00:56:19,000 --> 00:56:22,000
Why not?

1090
00:56:22,000 --> 00:56:24,000
It wouldn't work,
Lyddie.

1091
00:56:24,000 --> 00:56:25,000
Where we going
to put him?

1092
00:56:25,000 --> 00:56:27,000
We're building a house.

1093
00:56:27,000 --> 00:56:29,000
She doesn't think she's
going to make it that long.

1094
00:56:29,000 --> 00:56:32,000
We have a spare room.
We can fix it up.

1095
00:56:32,000 --> 00:56:35,000
It's not a practical idea.

1096
00:56:35,000 --> 00:56:36,000
Why not?

1097
00:56:36,000 --> 00:56:37,000
Because we're not set up for it.

1098
00:56:37,000 --> 00:56:39,000
We both work.
Who's going to look after him?

1099
00:56:39,000 --> 00:56:41,000
You have to make plans
for things like this.

1100
00:56:41,000 --> 00:56:43,000
It takes time.
Oh, come on, Sam.

1101
00:56:43,000 --> 00:56:45,000
I don't think this decision
is about being practical.

1102
00:56:45,000 --> 00:56:47,000
We've thought about this
for one night, okay?

1103
00:56:47,000 --> 00:56:49,000
It's a huge responsibility.

1104
00:56:49,000 --> 00:56:51,000
We've thought about having
kids for a long time.

1105
00:56:51,000 --> 00:56:53,000
What about Val?
I think Val's a good idea.

1106
00:56:53,000 --> 00:56:56,000
Her husband's out of work.

1107
00:56:56,000 --> 00:56:57,000
I don't think she can.

1108
00:56:57,000 --> 00:56:59,000
Well, then there's
the Grubers.

1109
00:56:59,000 --> 00:57:00,000
There's, there's
lots of people.

1110
00:57:00,000 --> 00:57:02,000
Why don't we just see
how she does?

1111
00:57:02,000 --> 00:57:03,000
Maybe she's wrong.

1112
00:57:03,000 --> 00:57:05,000
She could live
for another year.

1113
00:57:05,000 --> 00:57:08,000
She could live
for two years.

1114
00:57:08,000 --> 00:57:09,000
In the meantime,
I've got to go

1115
00:57:09,000 --> 00:57:10,000
inoculate the Holden
pigs, okay?

1116
00:57:10,000 --> 00:57:12,000
We'll find somebody.

1117
00:57:23,000 --> 00:57:24,000
Hi, Trooper.

1118
00:57:24,000 --> 00:57:27,000
Hey. Is Sam here?

1119
00:57:27,000 --> 00:57:29,000
He'll be back soon.

1120
00:57:31,000 --> 00:57:33,000
Lydia,

1121
00:57:33,000 --> 00:57:36,000
I'm sorry
I ran off like that.

1122
00:57:36,000 --> 00:57:40,000
It wasn't very
professional of me.

1123
00:57:40,000 --> 00:57:41,000
Well, you know,

1124
00:57:41,000 --> 00:57:46,000
I could use some professional
help with this fellow.

1125
00:57:46,000 --> 00:57:48,000
You want to hold him?
Hold him by the collar.

1126
00:57:48,000 --> 00:57:49,000
Okay.

1127
00:57:49,000 --> 00:57:50,000
Give him some comfort.

1128
00:57:53,000 --> 00:57:55,000
Sunny's having
his operation, huh?

1129
00:57:55,000 --> 00:57:56,000
Yup.

1130
00:57:56,000 --> 00:57:58,000
Is he going
to be okay?

1131
00:57:58,000 --> 00:58:00,000
He'll be great.

1132
00:58:01,000 --> 00:58:04,000
That's good. I was worried.

1133
00:58:11,000 --> 00:58:13,000
You ever think
of having more kids?

1134
00:58:13,000 --> 00:58:15,000
Beyond the two
little hellions

1135
00:58:15,000 --> 00:58:16,000
we're raising now,
you mean?

1136
00:58:16,000 --> 00:58:17,000
Yeah.

1137
00:58:17,000 --> 00:58:20,000
Why do you ask?

1138
00:58:20,000 --> 00:58:21,000
Just wondering.

1139
00:58:22,000 --> 00:58:23,000
You been talking to Naomi?

1140
00:58:23,000 --> 00:58:25,000
No. About what?

1141
00:58:25,000 --> 00:58:26,000
Lydia been talking
to Naomi?

1142
00:58:26,000 --> 00:58:28,000
Not that I know of. Why?

1143
00:58:31,000 --> 00:58:34,000
Naomi's pregnant.

1144
00:58:34,000 --> 00:58:36,000
Congratulations.

1145
00:58:36,000 --> 00:58:38,000
(laughs)
Thanks,

1146
00:58:38,000 --> 00:58:41,000
but I don't know how
we're going to do it.

1147
00:58:41,000 --> 00:58:43,000
We're barely making it
now on two teachers' salaries.

1148
00:58:43,000 --> 00:58:47,000
Yeah, it's not easy.

1149
00:58:47,000 --> 00:58:48,000
You and Lydia
thinking of...?

1150
00:58:48,000 --> 00:58:50,000
No. Not yet.

1151
00:58:50,000 --> 00:58:53,000
You still remember how?

1152
00:58:53,000 --> 00:58:55,000
It'll come back to me.

1153
00:58:57,000 --> 00:59:00,000
Sam, come on.
What'd you ask me for?

1154
00:59:02,000 --> 00:59:04,000
For Dee Dee.

1155
00:59:04,000 --> 00:59:05,000
(thunder crashes)

1156
00:59:23,000 --> 00:59:25,000
Sorry I'm late.

1157
00:59:25,000 --> 00:59:27,000
Oh, you're
never too late.

1158
00:59:27,000 --> 00:59:30,000
We were just going to start
to read our messages

1159
00:59:30,000 --> 00:59:32,000
we're putting
into our gift boxes, right?

1160
00:59:32,000 --> 00:59:33,000
Rosemary, do you want
to go first?

1161
00:59:33,000 --> 00:59:35,000
Oh, sure,
it's always me.

1162
00:59:35,000 --> 00:59:38,000
Oh, this is for
my brother-in-law Jack,

1163
00:59:38,000 --> 00:59:40,000
who is a real... pill.

1164
00:59:40,000 --> 00:59:43,000
Well, he is.

1165
00:59:43,000 --> 00:59:44,000
"Jack be nimble,

1166
00:59:44,000 --> 00:59:45,000
"Jack be quick,

1167
00:59:45,000 --> 00:59:47,000
"Jack jump over
the candlestick.

1168
00:59:47,000 --> 00:59:49,000
"But don't burn
your rear

1169
00:59:49,000 --> 00:59:50,000
"or you will see

1170
00:59:50,000 --> 00:59:52,000
exactly the pain
you are to me."

1171
00:59:52,000 --> 00:59:54,000
(laughing)

1172
00:59:54,000 --> 00:59:57,000
Not exactly what I had
in mind, but it works.

1173
00:59:57,000 --> 00:59:59,000
You don't know Jack.

1174
01:00:01,000 --> 01:00:03,000
(siren wailing)

1175
01:00:03,000 --> 01:00:05,000
(phone ringing)

1176
01:00:05,000 --> 01:00:07,000
Don't get excited.

1177
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:09,000
Remember last week
when the cat, like,

1178
01:00:09,000 --> 01:00:11,000
went through an alarm
and went all over the place.

1179
01:00:11,000 --> 01:00:14,000
It happens all the time.
Constantly.

1180
01:00:14,000 --> 01:00:16,000
Doc... it's
your new house.

1181
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:17,000
Come on, Dennis,

1182
01:00:17,000 --> 01:00:19,000
I'll give you a ride...
ALL:
Oh no!

1183
01:00:37,000 --> 01:00:40,000
I'm so sorry, Lydia.

1184
01:00:40,000 --> 01:00:42,000
It's just the framing.

1185
01:00:42,000 --> 01:00:46,000
It's not even a house, yet.

1186
01:00:46,000 --> 01:00:47,000
It's a dream.

1187
01:00:50,000 --> 01:00:53,000
Maybe we can dream it again.

1188
01:01:01,000 --> 01:01:03,000
RICK:
I kept the generator
going to run the pump.

1189
01:01:03,000 --> 01:01:05,000
I was afraid it was
going to flood.

1190
01:01:05,000 --> 01:01:07,000
It must have been
an electrical short.

1191
01:01:07,000 --> 01:01:08,000
I'm sorry.

1192
01:01:08,000 --> 01:01:10,000
LYDIA:
It's not your fault, Rick.

1193
01:01:10,000 --> 01:01:11,000
It was an accident.

1194
01:01:11,000 --> 01:01:14,000
When can we
start rebuilding?

1195
01:01:14,000 --> 01:01:16,000
RICK:
I'll have to clean
this mess up.

1196
01:01:16,000 --> 01:01:18,000
Labor Day is coming soon.

1197
01:01:18,000 --> 01:01:19,000
I say we wait
until spring.

1198
01:01:19,000 --> 01:01:21,000
Once the bad
weather starts
we're just

1199
01:01:21,000 --> 01:01:22,000
going to have to stop.

1200
01:01:22,000 --> 01:01:23,000
What do you think, Sam?

1201
01:01:26,000 --> 01:01:29,000
(crashing)

1202
01:01:55,000 --> 01:01:57,000
Sam?

1203
01:01:57,000 --> 01:01:59,000
Talk to me.

1204
01:02:02,000 --> 01:02:08,000
I had Rick do the house because
he's so... meticulous.

1205
01:02:08,000 --> 01:02:13,000
Every nail, every joint,
every angle...

1206
01:02:13,000 --> 01:02:17,000
just so.

1207
01:02:18,000 --> 01:02:21,000
I had him prepare
the house for a hurricane.

1208
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:22,000
Did I tell you that?

1209
01:02:22,000 --> 01:02:24,000
When was the last time there was

1210
01:02:24,000 --> 01:02:25,000
a hurricane around here?

1211
01:02:25,000 --> 01:02:26,000
I don't know.

1212
01:02:26,000 --> 01:02:28,000
A hundred years?

1213
01:02:31,000 --> 01:02:34,000
He was going
to truss the gables,

1214
01:02:34,000 --> 01:02:36,000
reinforce the garage door,

1215
01:02:36,000 --> 01:02:39,000
put a special adhesive
on the shingles...

1216
01:02:39,000 --> 01:02:41,000
You can't protect
against everything.

1217
01:02:41,000 --> 01:02:44,000
Not everything.

1218
01:02:44,000 --> 01:02:47,000
But everything you
can think of.

1219
01:02:47,000 --> 01:02:50,000
But you can't think
of everything either.

1220
01:02:50,000 --> 01:02:53,000
It was a freak accident.

1221
01:02:53,000 --> 01:02:57,000
My mother was so afraid
of hurricanes.

1222
01:02:57,000 --> 01:03:00,000
I don't blame her.

1223
01:03:00,000 --> 01:03:04,000
Nah, she was afraid
of pretty much everything.

1224
01:03:06,000 --> 01:03:08,000
Every time my dad would
leave on a sales trip,

1225
01:03:08,000 --> 01:03:10,000
he'd make sure we had
everything we needed.

1226
01:03:10,000 --> 01:03:12,000
Check the tires,
check the house,

1227
01:03:12,000 --> 01:03:14,000
the rain gutters,
the shutters,

1228
01:03:14,000 --> 01:03:15,000
did we have enough firewood,

1229
01:03:15,000 --> 01:03:17,000
and on and on and on.

1230
01:03:17,000 --> 01:03:18,000
And still, this woman,

1231
01:03:18,000 --> 01:03:20,000
she was afraid.

1232
01:03:20,000 --> 01:03:21,000
Of what?

1233
01:03:21,000 --> 01:03:23,000
Oh, you name it.

1234
01:03:23,000 --> 01:03:26,000
I used to hear her walking
around the house late at night,

1235
01:03:26,000 --> 01:03:30,000
making sure all the windows
were locked.

1236
01:03:30,000 --> 01:03:32,000
And every time
I'd leave the house,

1237
01:03:32,000 --> 01:03:34,000
my mother would ask me
if I had enough money?

1238
01:03:34,000 --> 01:03:37,000
Where are you going?

1239
01:03:37,000 --> 01:03:40,000
Are your socks warm enough?

1240
01:03:40,000 --> 01:03:43,000
I used to think I could
actually hear...

1241
01:03:43,000 --> 01:03:44,000
her worrying.

1242
01:03:44,000 --> 01:03:48,000
It got to the point
where I didn't even
want to leave the house.

1243
01:03:48,000 --> 01:03:51,000
It was easier
just to stay at home.

1244
01:03:58,000 --> 01:03:59,000
If it hadn't been for Dee Dee,

1245
01:03:59,000 --> 01:04:01,000
I probably would have never
left the yard.

1246
01:04:01,000 --> 01:04:04,000
She sounds like she was
a good friend to have.

1247
01:04:06,000 --> 01:04:09,000
She was more than that.

1248
01:04:12,000 --> 01:04:16,000
She was my friend,

1249
01:04:16,000 --> 01:04:18,000
my sister...

1250
01:04:24,000 --> 01:04:26,000
(sobbing)

1251
01:04:33,000 --> 01:04:36,000
Do you...

1252
01:04:36,000 --> 01:04:39,000
do you think I'd be
a good father?

1253
01:04:39,000 --> 01:04:43,000
Sam, yes.

1254
01:04:46,000 --> 01:04:48,000
Yes, I do.

1255
01:04:48,000 --> 01:04:52,000
Then let's take him.

1256
01:04:54,000 --> 01:04:57,000
Are you sure?

1257
01:05:16,000 --> 01:05:18,000
(doorbell ringing)

1258
01:05:28,000 --> 01:05:29,000
Hi.
Hi.

1259
01:05:29,000 --> 01:05:30,000
Hey.

1260
01:05:30,000 --> 01:05:31,000
Can we come in?

1261
01:05:31,000 --> 01:05:32,000
Sure.

1262
01:05:40,000 --> 01:05:42,000
What's up?

1263
01:05:42,000 --> 01:05:45,000
Where's Troop?

1264
01:05:45,000 --> 01:05:49,000
He's upstairs playing
with Chewbacca.

1265
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:08,000
We want to take him.

1266
01:06:11,000 --> 01:06:12,000
Are you sure?

1267
01:06:12,000 --> 01:06:14,000
Yeah.

1268
01:06:14,000 --> 01:06:15,000
When the time comes.

1269
01:06:15,000 --> 01:06:18,000
We're still hoping it won't.

1270
01:06:20,000 --> 01:06:22,000
I don't know what to say.

1271
01:06:22,000 --> 01:06:24,000
You don't have
to say anything.

1272
01:06:24,000 --> 01:06:27,000
I couldn't have even
hoped for this.

1273
01:06:28,000 --> 01:06:32,000
Oh, Sam, I'm so
proud of you.

1274
01:06:32,000 --> 01:06:34,000
Oh, we're both crazy about him.

1275
01:06:34,000 --> 01:06:38,000
That's great, but that's not
why I'm proud of you.

1276
01:06:38,000 --> 01:06:39,000
Okay, why are
you proud of me?

1277
01:06:39,000 --> 01:06:40,000
Because you married well.

1278
01:06:46,000 --> 01:06:48,000
I want to have a party.

1279
01:06:48,000 --> 01:06:49,000
A big one.

1280
01:06:49,000 --> 01:06:51,000
A party?

1281
01:06:51,000 --> 01:06:54,000
Might be my last chance.

1282
01:07:24,000 --> 01:07:26,000
Hey, Trooper, can I come in?

1283
01:07:26,000 --> 01:07:28,000
Uh-huh.

1284
01:07:32,000 --> 01:07:34,000
Did you have fun

1285
01:07:34,000 --> 01:07:35,000
with Rosemary today?

1286
01:07:35,000 --> 01:07:37,000
Mm-hmm.

1287
01:07:37,000 --> 01:07:39,000
Want to snuggle?

1288
01:07:58,000 --> 01:08:00,000
Remember how we always
said we'd hope

1289
01:08:00,000 --> 01:08:02,000
for the best when
I got sick?

1290
01:08:02,000 --> 01:08:05,000
Yeah.

1291
01:08:05,000 --> 01:08:10,000
Well, sometimes the best
doesn't happen.

1292
01:08:10,000 --> 01:08:15,000
And then, we have
to make other plans.

1293
01:08:15,000 --> 01:08:17,000
We have to make the best
of things as they are.

1294
01:08:21,000 --> 01:08:26,000
So, it looks like the best
isn't going to happen.

1295
01:08:34,000 --> 01:08:37,000
And if I'm not going
to be around...

1296
01:08:39,000 --> 01:08:42,000
...if I'm not
going to be around,

1297
01:08:42,000 --> 01:08:45,000
we're going to have to find
a place for you, Troop.

1298
01:08:45,000 --> 01:08:46,000
I don't want to.

1299
01:08:46,000 --> 01:08:49,000
I know, baby.

1300
01:08:49,000 --> 01:08:52,000
But we got to make
the best of things, don't we?

1301
01:08:52,000 --> 01:08:55,000
Maybe... maybe
my dad will come back.

1302
01:08:55,000 --> 01:08:57,000
Oh, Troop.

1303
01:08:57,000 --> 01:09:00,000
He, he could.

1304
01:09:00,000 --> 01:09:02,000
It's been a
very long time.

1305
01:09:02,000 --> 01:09:06,000
But he still could, Mom.

1306
01:09:08,000 --> 01:09:11,000
But in the meantime,

1307
01:09:11,000 --> 01:09:16,000
we have to find a place for you
where you'll be safe and happy.

1308
01:09:16,000 --> 01:09:17,000
Where people love you.

1309
01:09:17,000 --> 01:09:20,000
And they'll take
care of you.

1310
01:09:28,000 --> 01:09:31,000
You know, Sam and Lydia?

1311
01:09:31,000 --> 01:09:33,000
They love you very much.

1312
01:09:33,000 --> 01:09:34,000
Do you know that?

1313
01:09:36,000 --> 01:09:39,000
I know it.

1314
01:09:39,000 --> 01:09:42,000
Do you know how I know it?

1315
01:09:46,000 --> 01:09:51,000
'Cause they said that if
anything happened to me,

1316
01:09:51,000 --> 01:09:55,000
if I didn't get
better,

1317
01:09:55,000 --> 01:09:59,000
that they'd love to
have you live with them.

1318
01:09:59,000 --> 01:10:00,000
How would you feel
about that?

1319
01:10:00,000 --> 01:10:02,000
I don't want to, Mom.

1320
01:10:02,000 --> 01:10:04,000
I know, baby.

1321
01:10:04,000 --> 01:10:06,000
But as long as
we're talking about

1322
01:10:06,000 --> 01:10:07,000
making the best of things...

1323
01:10:07,000 --> 01:10:09,000
can you think of a place
you'd rather be?

1324
01:10:16,000 --> 01:10:18,000
Do you like them, Troop?

1325
01:10:26,000 --> 01:10:28,000
I like them very much.

1326
01:10:28,000 --> 01:10:33,000
In fact, I can't think of
anyone I'd rather you be with.

1327
01:10:33,000 --> 01:10:35,000
Can you?

1328
01:10:42,000 --> 01:10:44,000
Can we still hope?

1329
01:10:44,000 --> 01:10:47,000
Hope what?

1330
01:10:47,000 --> 01:10:50,000
That you'll get better.

1331
01:10:50,000 --> 01:10:53,000
Come here.

1332
01:10:55,000 --> 01:10:58,000
Yeah, we can still hope.

1333
01:10:58,000 --> 01:11:02,000
I'm still going
to hope then.

1334
01:11:02,000 --> 01:11:04,000
Me, too.

1335
01:11:13,000 --> 01:11:17,000
(indistinct conversations)

1336
01:11:38,000 --> 01:11:41,000
Have you been
taken care of?

1337
01:11:41,000 --> 01:11:42,000
Did you get something?

1338
01:11:42,000 --> 01:11:44,000
Oh, you did get something.

1339
01:11:44,000 --> 01:11:45,000
Excellent.

1340
01:11:45,000 --> 01:11:47,000
Who else?
Who else needs their drinks?

1341
01:12:08,000 --> 01:12:11,000
DEE DEE:
I'm going to sit down.

1342
01:12:11,000 --> 01:12:13,000
Yeah, go sit down.
Go on.

1343
01:12:13,000 --> 01:12:14,000
I'll, I'll fix the table.

1344
01:12:14,000 --> 01:12:17,000
I'll keep it going.
Go on.

1345
01:12:29,000 --> 01:12:31,000
Ladies and gentlemen,
